SAMPLE 1 — Clean case: one group splits into two topics
The group (from network graph)
Focal CUI: Peanut allergy
GROUP = { Peanut allergy, Tree nut allergy, Food allergy, Anaphylaxis, Allergy }
Each member's full family tree (MRREL) with IC at every level
Peanut allergy (0.92)  → Food allergy (0.62) → Allergy (0.40) → Hypersensitivity (0.22) → Disease (0.05)
Tree nut allergy (0.90)→ Food allergy (0.62) → Allergy (0.40) → ...
Food allergy (0.62)    → Allergy (0.40) → Hypersensitivity (0.22) → Disease (0.05)
Anaphylaxis (0.70)     → Allergy (0.40) → Hypersensitivity (0.22) → Disease (0.05)
Allergy (0.40)         → Hypersensitivity (0.22) → Disease (0.05)
Climb each member — keep ONLY in-group parents, apply IC floor (0.30), pick highest IC
Peanut allergy:
Food allergy (0.62)      → in group ✅, IC≥0.30 ✅
Allergy (0.40)           → in group ✅, IC≥0.30 ✅ but lower
Hypersensitivity (0.22)  → not in group ❌ (and below floor anyway)
Disease (0.05)           → not in group ❌
WINNER = Food allergy (0.62)   ← highest IC among in-group
Tree nut allergy:
Food allergy (0.62) ✅ in group, highest → WINNER
Allergy (0.40) in group, lower → skipped
WINNER = Food allergy (0.62)
Anaphylaxis:
Allergy (0.40) ✅ in group, IC≥0.30 → WINNER  (Food allergy is NOT its ancestor)
Hypersensitivity (0.22) not in group ❌
WINNER = Allergy (0.40)
Food allergy:
Allergy (0.40) ✅ in group → WINNER
WINNER = Allergy (0.40)
Result — two topics from one group
TOPIC "Food allergy" (anchor IC 0.62)
   { Peanut allergy, Tree nut allergy, Food allergy }

TOPIC "Allergy" (anchor IC 0.40)
   { Anaphylaxis, Food allergy }
Why two: the nut allergies climbed to Food allergy (specific), while Anaphylaxis had no Food-allergy ancestor so it stopped at Allergy. Different in-group parents → different topics. Clean and correct.

SAMPLE 2 — Edge case: a member with NO good in-group parent
The group (from network graph)
Focal CUI: Rectal cancer
GROUP = { Rectal cancer, Colon cancer, Colorectal cancer, Malignant neoplasm, Constipation }
Note: Constipation got pulled in by the network (it co-occurs in colorectal notes) but it's clinically a different axis.
Family trees with IC
Rectal cancer (0.88)      → Colorectal cancer (0.66) → Malignant neoplasm (0.45) → Neoplasm (0.20) → Disease (0.05)
Colon cancer (0.87)       → Colorectal cancer (0.66) → Malignant neoplasm (0.45) → ...
Colorectal cancer (0.66)  → Malignant neoplasm (0.45) → Neoplasm (0.20) → Disease (0.05)
Constipation (0.78)       → Symptom (0.30) → Clinical finding (0.08) → ...   (a DIFFERENT branch)
Climb each member
Rectal cancer:
Colorectal cancer (0.66) ✅ in group, IC≥0.30, highest → WINNER
Malignant neoplasm (0.45) in group ✅ but lower → skipped
Neoplasm (0.20) not in group ❌ (also below floor)
WINNER = Colorectal cancer (0.66)
Colon cancer:
Colorectal cancer (0.66) ✅ → WINNER
WINNER = Colorectal cancer (0.66)
Colorectal cancer:
Malignant neoplasm (0.45) ✅ in group → WINNER
WINNER = Malignant neoplasm (0.45)
Constipation — THE EDGE CASE:
Constipation's ancestors: Symptom (0.30), Clinical finding (0.08), ...
Is Symptom in the group?          NO ❌
Is Clinical finding in the group? NO ❌
→ NO in-group ancestor at all
→ Constipation gets NO anchor from this group → it is UNGROUPED here
Constipation was a network-neighbor (co-occurs with colorectal cancer) but its family tree shares no parent with the cancer concepts. So it doesn't join any cancer topic. Correct — constipation isn't a cancer.
Result
TOPIC "Colorectal cancer" (anchor IC 0.66)
   { Rectal cancer, Colon cancer, Colorectal cancer }

TOPIC "Malignant neoplasm" (anchor IC 0.45)
   { Colorectal cancer }

Constipation → UNGROUPED in this group
   (it will get its own topic later when IT is the focal point,
    anchoring to "Symptom" or its own neighborhood)
